<s> DELEGATIONS FROM THE U. S. AND THE CUBAN GOVERNMENTS PLAN TO SIT DOWN IN NEW YORK CITY LATER THIS WEEK TO TALK ABOUT MIGRATION BETWEEN THE TWO COUNTRIES </s>
<s> THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION IS READY TO GRANT THE CUBANS NEW OPPORTUNITIES TO IMMIGRATE LEGALLY TO THE U. S. </s>
<s> IN EXCHANGE THE CUBAN GOVERNMENT WOULD HAVE TO AGREE TO HALT THE EXODUS OF PEOPLE LEAVING THE ISLAND ON FLIMSY RAFTS AND BOATS FOR THE COAST OF FLORIDA </s>
<s> THE CUBANS HAVE SAID THEY WILL COOPERATE BUT THEY WANT TO BROADEN THE TALKS TO INCLUDE THE THIRTY YEAR OLD U. S. TRADE EMBARGO WITH CUBA AND OTHER ISSUES </s>
<s> NPR'S TOM GJELTEN REPORTS </s>
<s> THE DIFFERENCE IN U. S. AND CUBAN PERSPECTIVES ON THE NEW YORK TALKS IS EVIDENT IN THE DELEGATIONS EACH GOVERNMENT IS SENDING </s>
<s> THE CUBAN SIDE WILL BE LED BY RICARDO ALARCON A SEASONED DIPLOMAT WHO WAS FORMERLY CUBA'S AMBASSADOR TO THE UNITED NATIONS AND LATER FOREIGN MINISTER </s>
<s> HE IS ONE OF FIDEL CASTRO'S TOP CONFIDANTS AND HIS SELECTION AS DELEGATION LEADER SHOWS THAT CASTRO WANTS THESE TALKS TO BE SUBSTANTIVE AND WIDE RANGING </s>
<s> THE U. S. TEAM WILL BE LED BY MIKE SKOLL A DEPUTY ASSISTANT SECRETARY IN THE STATE DEPARTMENT AND SEVERAL NOTCHES BELOW ALARCON IN THE DIPLOMATIC HIERARCHY </s>
<s> BY SENDING A FAIRLY LOW LEVEL DELEGATION THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION IS SAYING IT INTENDS TO KEEP THE NEW YORK TALKS FOCUSED ON THE TECHNICALITIES OF IMMIGRATION AND LITTLE ELSE </s>
<s> STATE DEPARTMENT SPOKESMAN MIKE MCCURRY SAYS HE IS AWARE THE CUBANS MIGHT NOT BE SATISFIED WITH A NARROWLY LIMITED AGENDA </s>
<s> THEY BELIEVE THAT THERE ARE OTHER ISSUES THAT MAY BE PERTINENT TO THIS DISCUSSION SO WE EXPECT THAT THEY MAY BRING THOSE UP </s>
<s> FROM THE POINT OF THE UNITED STATES' VIEW OUR DETERMINATION IS TO KEEP THESE TALKS FOCUSED ON THE ONE SUBJECT THAT WE CAN HAVE SOME TYPE OF DIALOGUE WITH CUBA ABOUT AND THAT IS THE SUBJECT OF MIGRATION </s>
<s> THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION MCCURRY SAID HOPES THE CUBAN GOVERNMENT WILL AGREE TO LIMIT ILLEGAL IMMIGRATION FROM CUBA IF THE OPPORTUNITIES FOR LEGAL IMMIGRATION ARE INCREASED </s>
<s> MUCH OF THE NEGOTIATION IN NEW YORK IS EXPECTED TO FOCUS ON THE NUMBER OF CUBANS THAT CAN APPLY FOR IMMIGRATION TO THE UNITED STATES EACH YEAR </s>
<s> THERE ARE ANYWHERE THE NUMBER HAS BEEN UP TO TWENTY EIGHT THOUSAND SLOTS OR TRANSFERS THAT HAVE BEEN NEGOTIATED AND THERE ARE THINGS THAT WE CAN TALK ABOUT WITH THE CUBAN GOVERNMENT THAT WOULD RELATE TO THAT </s>
<s> THE TWENTY EIGHT THOUSAND SLOTS THAT MCCURRY MENTIONS COMPRISE JUST ONE CATEGORY OF CUBANS WHO MIGHT BE ABLE TO IMMIGRATE TO THE UNITED STATES EACH YEAR </s>
<s> IT DOES NOT INCLUDE CUBANS WHO CLAIM THEY ARE PERSECUTED AND SEEK POLITICAL ASYLUM IN THE UNITED STATES NOR DOES IT INCLUDE THOSE CUBANS WHOSE CHILDREN OR SPOUSES ARE U. S. CITIZENS THEY CAN COME TO THE UNITED STATES AUTOMATICALLY </s>
<s> THE NUMERICALLY RESTRICTED CATEGORY IS FOR CUBANS WHO WANT TO JOIN OTHER FAMILY MEMBERS IN THE UNITED STATES BROTHERS SISTERS OR PARENTS FOR EXAMPLE </s>
<s> FOR THE PAST SEVERAL YEARS ONLY ABOUT THREE THOUSAND SUCH VISAS WERE APPROVED ANNUALLY FAR BELOW THE TWENTY THOUSAND TO TWENTY EIGHT THOUSAND TECHNICALLY ALLOWABLE </s>
<s> THE DISCREPANCY IS MISLEADING HOWEVER </s>
<s> THE NUMBER OF IMMIGRANTS FROM AROUND THE WORLD IN THIS RESTRICTED CATEGORY WHO CAN ENTER THE UNITED STATES EACH YEAR IS FIXED BY LAW AT AROUND TWO HUNDRED TWENTY FIVE THOUSAND </s>
<s> WOULD BE IMMIGRANTS FROM CUBA WHOSE VISA REQUESTS ARE APPROVED MUST WAIT UNTIL THOSE PEOPLE AHEAD OF THEM IN LINE FROM WHATEVER COUNTRY ARE ADMITTED </s>
<s> DUKE AUSTIN SPOKESMAN FOR THE IMMIGRATION AND NATURALIZATION SERVICE POINTS OUT THAT THE U. S. CONGRESS LIMITED CUBA TO TWENTY THOUSAND IMMIGRANTS A YEAR LATER RAISED TO TWENTY EIGHT THOUSAND BUT IT DID NOT MEAN THAT THAT MANY SPACES WERE RESERVED FOR CUBAN IMMIGRANTS </s>
<s> AND THEY SAID CUBA YOU WILL BE RESTRICTED TO THE SAME CEILING LIKE ALL OTHER COUNTRIES IN THE WORLD </s>
<s> IT'S NOT AN ORGANIZATION BY CEILING SO IT DIDN'T SAY YOU GET TWENTY THOUSAND IT SAID YOU CANNOT GET ANY MORE THAN TWENTY THOUSAND </s>
<s> THE APPROXIMATELY THREE THOUSAND CUBANS WHO IMMIGRATED LAST YEAR TO THE U. S. AUSTIN SAYS WERE THE MAXIMUM GIVEN THE WORLDWIDE QUOTA </s>
<s> CLINTON ADMINISTRATION NEGOTIATORS CANNOT ARBITRARILY CHANGE THAT NUMBER </s>
<s> THERE IS A TREMENDOUS DEMAND TO IMMIGRATE HERE THERE IS NO ABILITY TO FUDGE WITH THOSE NUMBERS </s>
<s> THERE IS NO ABILITY OF THE EXECUTIVE BRANCH OR THE STATE DEPARTMENT OR THE IMMIGRATION SERVICE TO START JUGGLING THOSE NUMBERS PREFERENTIALLY TO GET ONE COUNTRY MORE AND ANOTHER COUNTRY LESS </s>
<s> IT'S FIXED IN STATUTE </s>
<s> SO WHAT CAN THE U. S. STATE DEPARTMENT DISCUSS WITH THE CUBANS IN NEW YORK THIS WEEK </s>
<s> TWO THINGS FIRST THE ATTORNEY GENERAL DOES HAVE AUTHORITY TO TAKE PEOPLE OUT OF THE VISA LINE AND IN LEGAL TERMS PAROLE THEM INTO THE UNITED STATES BYPASSING THE NORMAL IMMIGRATION PROCEDURE </s>
<s> ADMINISTRATION SOURCES SAY THE STATE DEPARTMENT NEGOTIATORS WILL OFFER TO DO THIS FOR CUBANS SO THAT MORE CAN IMMIGRATE TO THE UNITED STATES THAN WOULD OTHERWISE BE PERMITTED </s>
<s> SECOND THE STATE DEPARTMENT CAN MAKE IT EASIER FOR CUBANS TO APPLY FOR POLITICAL ASYLUM IN THE STATES </s>
<s> MORE IMMIGRATION OFFICERS CAN BE SENT TO HAVANA TO INTERVIEW ASYLUM SEEKERS AND THE DEFINITION OF WHAT CONSTITUTES PERSECUTION CAN BE SOMEWHAT BROADENED SO THAT MORE CUBANS MEET THE CRITERIA </s>
<s> IN THESE TWO WAYS THE U. S. GOVERNMENT CAN MAKE IT POSSIBLE FOR THOUSANDS MORE CUBANS TO COME LEGALLY TO THE UNITED STATES EACH YEAR </s>
