<s> ATTORNEYS FOR C. N. N. AND OTHER NEWS MEDIA ORGANIZATIONS ARE EXPECTED TO ARGUE IN COURT TODAY AGAINST A PARTIAL GAG ORDER SUGGESTED BY JUDGE ITO </s>
<s> THE MEDIA HAVE FILED A MOTION CLAIMING THE EFFORT TO SUPPRESS INFORMATION IS UNCONSTITUTIONAL </s>
<s> CORRESPONDENT CHARLES FELDMAN HAS OUR REPORT </s>
<s> INFORMATION </s>
<s> IT'S WHAT REPORTERS WANT MOST TO GET ABOUT THE O. J. SIMPSON CASE AND WHAT THE JUDGE PRESIDING OVER THE TRIAL WOULD LIKE TO CONTROL </s>
<s> A GAG ORDER IS HOW JUDGE LANCE ITO WANTS TO ACCOMPLISH THIS </s>
<s> IT WOULD PRESCRIBE WHAT LAWYERS AND OTHERS INVOLVED CAN SAY PUBLICLY ABOUT THE CASE </s>
<s> BUT SOME CONSTITUTIONAL EXPERTS SAY JUDGE ITO MAY HAVE GONE MUCH TOO FAR SCULPTING A GAG ORDER THAT MAY BE UNPRECEDENTED IN SCOPE AND THEY SAY TURNING FIRST AMENDMENT LAW UPSIDE DOWN </s>
<s> WHILE JUDGES OFTEN TRY TO GAG LAWYERS FROM SPEAKING JUDGE ITO GOES MUCH FURTHER </s>
<s> HE WANTS ALL MOTIONS FILED WITH THE COURT TO BE UNDER SEAL </s>
<s> SAYING THAT EVERYTHING FILED WITH THE COURT WON'T BE SEEN BY THE PUBLIC AND BY THE PRESS IS ABSOLUTELY UNCONSTITUTIONAL </s>
<s> IT IS AN ATTEMPT TO REGULATE NOT THE ATTORNEYS IN THE CASE BUT TO REGULATE THE PRESS AND TO REGULATE THE MOST FUNDAMENTAL FREEDOM THE RIGHT OF FREEDOM OF SPEECH </s>
<s> WHEN ALL ELSE FAILS TO STOP UNWANTED LEAKS OF INFORMATION TO THE MEDIA JUDGES OFTEN RESORT TO GAG ORDERS </s>
<s> NEW YORK'S WORLD TRADE CENTER BOMBING CASE LAWYERS WERE SLAPPED WITH ONE BUT IT WAS THROWN OUT ON APPEAL </s>
<s> A GAG ORDER IN THE RODNEY KING CASE WAS ALSO OVERTURNED </s>
<s> IN FACT THE BROADER THE SCOPE OF THE GAG ORDER IN THE SIMPSON CASE EXPERTS SAY THE MORE LIKELY IT IS THAT AN APPEALS COURT WILL OVERTURN IT </s>
<s> WE DO OPERATE IN A SYSTEM THAT HAS OPEN TRIALS </s>
<s> WE DON'T SEQUESTER TRIALS IN LITTLE DARK ROOMS THAT ARE NOT OPEN TO THE PUBLIC EYE </s>
<s> AND THE BROADER HIS ORDER IS THE MORE IT MOVES US AWAY FROM AN OPEN TRIAL TO SOMETHING THAT IS DONE IN A SPANISH INQUISITION STYLE WHICH OF COURSE IS ANATHEMA TO OUR WHOLE SYSTEM </s>
<s> ALREADY C. N. N. AND OTHER NEWS ORGANIZATIONS ARE CHALLENGING THE GAG ORDER </s>
<s> BUT THE EXTRAORDINARY NATURE OF THE SIMPSON CASE IS EVIDENT BY THE FACT THAT EVEN SOME JOURNALISTS FIND THEMSELVES IN THE UNCOMFORTABLE POSITION OF BACKING A GAG ORDER </s>
<s> I DON'T LIKE GAG ORDERS OR BARRIERS TO INFORMATION BUT I THINK THE JUDGE HAS A REAL PROBLEM HERE AND IT'S NOT ONLY TO ASSURE THAT O. J. SIMPSON GETS A FAIR TRIAL BUT THAT THE PUBLIC GETS A FAIR TRIAL </s>
<s> WHILE THE U. S. SUPREME COURT HAS AFFIRMED A NEVADA COURT RULING UPHOLDING A GAG ORDER IN THAT STATE EXPERTS SAY THE THINKING OF THE HIGH COURT ON THE BROADER ISSUE OF THE OVER ALL CONSTITUTIONALITY OF GAG ORDERS IS AS YET UNKNOWN </s>
<s> CHARLES FELDMAN C. N. N. LOS ANGELES </s>
