<s> A FEDERAL APPEALS COURT IN CALIFORNIA TODAY UPHELD A LOWER COURT'S REINSTATEMENT OF A GAY SAILOR </s>
<s> KEITH MEINHOLD WAS DISCHARGED AFTER HE SAID HE WAS A HOMOSEXUAL DURING A TELEVISION NEWS BROADCAST </s>
<s> NPR'S INA JAFFE REPORTS THAT WHILE THE RULING WAS GOOD NEWS FOR MEINHOLD IT DOES NOT PROVIDE SWEEPING CONSTITUTIONAL PROTECTION FOR GAYS IN THE MILITARY </s>
<s> WHAT PETTY OFFICER KEITH MEINHOLD SAID IN A NINETEEN NINETY TWO A. B. C. NEWSCAST WAS THIS YES I AM IN FACT GAY </s>
<s> TODAY THE NINTH CIRCUIT COURT OF APPEALS RULED THAT THE NAVY WAS WRONG IN DISCHARGING HIM FOR MAKING THAT STATEMENT </s>
<s> MEINHOLD HAD BEEN DISCHARGED UNDER AN OLD POLICY THAT BANNED HOMOSEXUALS FROM SERVING IN THE MILITARY PERIOD </s>
<s> THE LOWER COURT HAD FOUND THAT POLICY UNCONSTITUTIONAL NOT ONLY IN MEINHOLD'S CASE BUT FOR ALL SERVICE PERSONNEL BUT THE COURT OF APPEALS RULING WAS NARROWER </s>
<s> THE APPEALS COURT WROTE WE DEFER TO THE NAVY'S JUDGMENT THAT THE PRESENCE OF PERSONS WHO ENGAGE IN HOMOSEXUAL CONDUCT IMPAIRS THE ACCOMPLISHMENT OF THE MILITARY MISSION </s>
<s> BUT MEINHOLD'S SIMPLE STATEMENT THAT HE IS GAY DOES NOT INDICATE A DESIRE OR INTENT TO ENGAGE IN THAT CONDUCT SAID THE COURT </s>
<s> WHILE THE APPEALS COURT UPHELD MEINHOLD'S REINSTATEMENT IT DID NOT UPHOLD THE LOWER COURT'S RULING THAT THE OLD BAN ON HOMOSEXUALS SERVING IN THE MILITARY WAS UNCONSTITUTIONAL AND SHOULD BE STRUCK DOWN </s>
<s> BEATRICE DORN IS THE LEGAL DIRECTOR OF THE LAMBDA LEGAL DEFENSE AND EDUCATION FUND WHICH WAS NOT DIRECTLY INVOLVED IN THIS CASE </s>
<s> SHE SAYS THAT THOUGH THE RULING IS NARROW IT IS STILL CAUSE FOR OPTIMISM </s>
<s> I'M EXTREMELY HEARTENED THAT A COURT SUCH AS THE NINTH CIRCUIT HAS AFFIRMED THE REINSTATEMENT OF AN OPENLY GAY MEMBER OF THE MILITARY IN ITSELF </s>
<s> I MEAN THERE WAS NOT THAT LONG AGO THAT WE REALLY COULD NOT HAVE IMAGINED THAT AND I THINK THAT'S A HEARTENING THING IN AND OF ITSELF QUITE ASIDE FROM PICKING APART THE TECHNICAL WAYS THAT THE COURT MAY HAVE BOUGHT SOME OF OUR ARGUMENTS AND NOT OTHERS </s>
<s> TODAY'S RULING DOES NOT AFFECT THE CURRENT POLICY ON GAY MEN AND LESBIANS SERVING IN THE MILITARY </s>
<s> THAT POLICY KNOWN AS DON'T ASK DON'T TELL WENT INTO EFFECT THIS PAST FEBRUARY </s>
<s> IT PROHIBITS THE MILITARY FROM ASKING SERVICE PERSONNEL ABOUT THEIR SEXUAL ORIENTATION AND PROHIBITS HOMOSEXUAL PERSONNEL FROM OPENLY DECLARING THEIR ORIENTATION </s>
<s> NEVERTHELESS DORN SAYS THE APPEALS COURT DECISION WILL HAVE AN EFFECT ON PENDING LEGAL CHALLENGES TO DON'T ASK DON'T TELL </s>
<s> OUR SYSTEM OF COURT DECISIONS IS THAT ONE A PROPOSITION ESTABLISHED IN ONE CASE IS PRECEDENT FOR THE NEXT AND THE NEXT AND SO TO THE EXTENT THAT THESE POLICIES ARE QUITE SIMILAR CERTAINLY WE WILL BE TAKING THE POSITIVE ASPECTS OF THIS DECISION AND ARGUING THAT THEY WILL SHOULD GUIDE THE COURT IN IN THE CASES THAT WE'RE LITIGATING UNDER THE NEW POLICY </s>
<s> BUT THOSE CASES WILL TAKE A WHILE TO COME TO COURT </s>
