<s> AS THE EXODUS OF REFUGEES FLEEING CUBA ESCALATES U. S. OFFICIALS MEET WITH THE DELEGATION FROM HAVANA TODAY IN NEW YORK </s>
<s> AMONG OTHER THINGS THEIR TALKS ARE TO CENTER ON STEMMING THE FLOW OF RAFTERS BY OPENING UP LEGAL IMMIGRATION </s>
<s> C. N. N. CORRESPONDENT BRIAN JENKINS IS NEAR THE U. S. MISSION TO THE U. N. WHERE THE TALKS ARE BEING HELD AND HE JOINS US THIS MORNING WITH MORE </s>
<s> GOOD MORNING BRIAN </s>
<s> GOOD MORNING BOB </s>
<s> THE TALKS SET TO START HERE IN ABOUT AN HOUR ARE TECHNICALLY A CONTINUATION OF MEETINGS ON IMMIGRATION ISSUES THAT BEGAN BACK IN NINETEEN EIGHTY FOUR AND HAVE CONTINUED AT THE RATE OF ABOUT TWO MEETINGS A YEAR </s>
<s> BUT IN THE MIDST OF THE HUGE EXODUS OF CUBAN REFUGEES BY SEA TO FLORIDA THIS IS A VITAL STEP IN TRYING TO RESOLVE THE CRISIS </s>
<s> THE CUBAN DELEGATION ARRIVED YESTERDAY AT THEIR MISSION TO THE U. N. HEADED BY ONE OF FIDEL CASTRO'S TOP GUNS IN DIPLOMACY RICARDO ALARCON </s>
<s> HE IS A FORMER FOREIGN MINISTER AND FORMERLY CUBA'S AMBASSADOR TO THE U. N. </s>
<s> HE ENGINEERED THE PASSAGE OF A U. N. RESOLUTION THREE YEARS AGO DENOUNCING THE UNITED STATES' THREE DECADE LONG ECONOMIC EMBARGO OF CUBA </s>
<s> ALARCON LEFT HIS DIPLOMATIC CAREER LAST YEAR TO BECOME PRESIDENT OF CUBA'S PARLIAMENT THE NATIONAL ASSEMBLY </s>
<s> HEADING UP THE U. S. DELEGATION IS CAREER DIPLOMAT MICHAEL SKOLE THE NUMBER TWO MAN IN THE STATE DEPARTMENT'S LATIN AMERICA DIVISION </s>
<s> HE SAYS THE UNITED STATES' GOAL IN THE TALKS IS TO END THE RAFTER OUTFLOW FROM CUBA AND TO INCREASE THE POSSIBILITY FOR SAFE AND LEGAL IMMIGRATION BY CUBANS </s>
<s> CURRENTLY ONLY A FEW THOUSAND CUBANS ARE ALLOWED INTO THE U. S. EACH YEAR </s>
<s> NOW THE CUBAN SIDE IS LOOKING FOR MUCH MORE FROM THESE MEETINGS </s>
<s> THEY WANT THESE MID LEVEL TALKS TO LEAD TO HIGHER LEVEL NEGOTIATIONS ON A NUMBER OF MAJOR ISSUES INCLUDING THE EASING OF U. S. TRADE SANCTIONS THE TRADE EMBARGO NEGOTIATIONS ON THE RETURN TO CUBAN CONTROL OF THE U. S. NAVAL BASE AT GUANTANAMO BAY AN END TO THE ANTI CASTRO BROADCASTS INTO CUBA ON U. S. GOVERNMENT RADIO AND THE REVERSAL OF THE LATEST U. S. SANCTIONS INCLUDING THE BAN ON U. S. DOLLAR TRANSFERS AND CHARTER FLIGHTS TO CUBA </s>
<s> THE U. S. WANTS CASTRO TO TAKE STEPS LEADING TO FREE ELECTIONS AND ECONOMIC REFORMS BUT U. S. OFFICIALS SAY THEY ARE READY TO ACCEPT SMALLER STEPS FIRST INCLUDING THE RELEASE OF POLITICAL PRISONERS PERMITTING THE PRESENCE OF POLITICAL DISSIDENTS AND A FREE PRESS AND TAKING BACK CUBAN CRIMINALS SENT TO THE U. S. DURING THE NINETEEN EIGHTY MARIEL BOATLIFT </s>
<s> THE U. S. IS ALSO EXPECTED TO DEMAND TO KNOW IF CUBA IS ALLOWING AND PERHAPS EVEN ENCOURAGING PRISONERS TO JOIN THE CURRENT EXODUS </s>
<s> SO A GOOD NUMBER OF ISSUES WILL BE LAID ON THE TABLE HERE TODAY </s>
<s> THE TALKS MAY GO INTO THE WEEKEND AND WE WILL BE HERE TO KEEP YOU UPDATED </s>
